üîπ 1. Edit your Service to use NodePort or LoadBalancer
Example Service with NodePort
yaml
Copy
Edit
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: my-grpc-service
spec:
  selector:
    app: my-grpc-app
  type: NodePort
  ports:
    - name: grpc
      port: 50051            # Service port
      targetPort: 50051      # Pod port
      protocol: TCP
      nodePort: 30051        # Fixed NodePort (optional)
‚úÖ After applying:

Your gRPC server is reachable on any node IP of your cluster:

kotlin
Copy
Edit
<node-external-ip>:30051
If you omit nodePort, OpenShift will pick a random port in the 30000‚Äì32767 range.

Example Service with LoadBalancer
If your OpenShift cluster is on a cloud (AWS/GCP/Azure) and supports LoadBalancer Services:

yaml
Copy
Edit
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: my-grpc-service
spec:
  selector:
    app: my-grpc-app
  type: LoadBalancer
  ports:
    - name: grpc
      port: 50051
      targetPort: 50051
      protocol: TCP
‚úÖ After applying:

OpenShift will provision a cloud LoadBalancer and give you an external IP/DNS.

Connect directly to:

makefile
Copy
Edit
<loadbalancer-ip>:50051
üîπ 2. Test connectivity
If NodePort:

bash
Copy
Edit
grpcurl -plaintext <node-external-ip>:30051 list
If LoadBalancer:

bash
Copy
Edit
grpcurl -plaintext <lb-ip>:50051 list
‚úÖ -plaintext is required because your gRPC server is not using TLS.

üîπ 3. Firewall / Security
Make sure:

Your cluster nodes are accessible on the NodePort range (30000‚Äì32767) or on the LoadBalancer port.

Check with your infra/network team if any firewall allows access.

‚ú® Summary
Type	Works With	How to connect
NodePort	Any cluster (on‚Äëprem or cloud)	<node-ip>:<nodePort>
LoadBalancer	Cloud clusters	<LB‚Äëip>:<port>

‚úÖ No need to modify your gRPC server
‚úÖ No need to handle TLS if you‚Äôre okay with plaintext

